Crowds recently marching in Caracas seemed smaller than earlier in the year. Maduro praising anything relating to the US ("dollarization") seems odd - especially since it's a repudiation of the use of the bolivar as the nation's currency - indicates to me a man more at ease than conditions would otherwise suggest. Guaido's followers seem tired - recent marching more akin to "once more unto the breach, dear friends"? And all is not well in La Paz post-Evo - with fuel blockages and military interventions and 20+ deaths - I'm not sure Venezuelans (civilians and military) want any part of that. I have a sense the opposition has chosen to wait him out for the rest of 2019. So I've dropped my percentage for a pre-2020 departure (departure by force unlikely) but still feel there's more than a slight chance of pre-2020 departure from self-exile (those now-aborted August/Sept Oslo negotiations have left in their wake back-channel communications) All this is speculation, regrettably. There appeared precious little from public sources that was relevant.
Very unlikely, but his death and a Christmas miracle are possible.

I was very surprised at the Evo Morales abdication/resignation/departure. The resulting pictures and sounds of unrest in Bolivia probably makes real to the Venezuelan military what an uncoordinated removal from power looks and sounds and smells like. It may also encourage those who resist the government that, if they act in similar manner, similar outcome is possible. While the military is probably still in Maduro's corner - they've also had another 8 months of behind-the-scenes pressures and incentives to act. And we now know that Maduro may have safe haven - Mexico. Speculation had always been Cuba - but I wonder if the Cuban government didn't give mixed signals as they weighed the likelihood and severity of more approbations from the US if they took in Maduro. Now there's a different glide path in evidence. Having a place to go always makes it easier to leave........

From the Economist: “Since Monday, representatives of Nicolás Maduro’s regime have been in secret talks with a delegation from the Venezuelan opposition in Barbados. They are attempting to find a solution to the political deadlock that has gripped the country for the last six months. The talks, which are mediated by Norway, are likely to be dominated by questions over the timing and framing of new presidential elections: namely whether President Maduro, widely accused of having rigged last year’s poll, would stand down in advance of any vote, and what the composition of the national electoral council will be. Juan Guaidó, the opposition leader who is recognised as interim president by most western democracies, has been criticised by some of his would-be supporters for falling into a “trap” of talking to representatives of a clique that has little intention of giving up power. His response is that the unpopular and nearly bankrupt Maduro government is much weaker than it might appear.“

I live in London but I'm originally from Venezuela, so I follow news from there very closely (also, I probably have some bias). While I think Maduro will cease to be president of Venezuela before the end of his latest period, I don't think it will happen this year, as he has control of the armed forces and the international community has little incentive to invade. However, the tension is so high in the country that any unexpected event could generate a chain reaction ending with Maduro ceasing to be president, which is why I think there is a small possibility this could happen in 2019.

Update: To me, it seems that Maduro has been able to handle the last period of tension in the country, he is still controlling the army and has not faced a concrete practical opposition by foreign countries, but only threats (for example, USA has never taken action). Guaidò (the leading opposer) has been isolated by Maduro and his fellows have not reached and many of Maduro opponents have abandoned the country. The international community is not giving anymore attention to the Venezuela situation, and the EU is simply pushing for a peaceful solution. Moreover, in the last days Maduro has signed an agreement with Huawei about improving 4G connection. This choice would have a twofold effect: linking even more Venezuela with Chine, a country that has always supported Maduro, and, above all, allows Maduro, in the long-term, to control even better the local communication networks. According to these facts (and the fact we are already at half June) I reshape drastically my forecast, predicting that Maduro won’t cease to be President in the short-term. However, in case of big changes during the second half on 2019, I assess to 10% the probability of Maduro ceasing to be president between 1 october and 31 december.

Oil production: OPEC secondary sources suggest Venezuelan oil production in May was 741,000 barrels per day. That is a decline of 35,000 bpd from April. The Maduro regime’s inability to restart oil production following major declines this year remains a key source of financial problems for them.

As June is close to be over, the percentage for Nicolas Maduro to cease to be President Venezuela will I leave to a 1% change. Moreover, the worst days of the crisis around Maduro are over, not at least because other incidents have taken precedence in international politics that require attention from the international community, therefore decreasing the factor of Maduro ceasing power due to international interference.

Update: In my last forecast on this question, I focused on factors that would initiate a coup and as it was rightly pointed out by other forecasters, this is naturally only one way in which Maduro’s presidency would cease. Another, challenge to his hold on power in Venezuela is the prospect of an uprising.

Maduro has continued to hold on to power and the oppositions momentum from the elections have passed. The US's threats have thus far been just that, likely due to Russia's public backing of Maduro. Furthermore, the EU and China are pushing hard for a peaceful resolution. However, Maduro will not willingly step down. Furthermore, Guaido's attempts of resistance have fallen flat and many political opponents have simply fled the country. Finally, public opposition to Maduro has decreased in the past weeks despite conditions continuing to deteriorate. At this moment in time it is looking like Maduro has successfully weathered the worst of it and in successfully cracking down on the opposition, making it even less likely that he'll cease to be president by the end of the year.

Update: Inching closer to June 30, and plots to overthrow Maduro have largely subsided. It is thus considered highly unlikely that Maduro will cease to be president within the next three week. For the reasons already covered, it is forecasted that Maduro will continue to be President of Venezuela until at least January 1, 2020. Smaller percentages are allocated to the time periods following June 3, accounting the for the possibility of an unforeseen event amounting to Maduro's removal. Based on coup and coup-attempt statistics and with Venezuela's instability, the further Maduro remains in power the more likely one will occur -- accounting for the increase in the percentage as the time frame moves further into the future.

As I was completely floored about how to go about this forecast, I chose to look closer at the One Earth Future Research and their CoupCast program that work to predict the likelihood of a coup attempt to occur by drawing on historical data and machine learning. The research program has identified six variables that are indicative of the potential of regime overthrow. The variables are the following: 1. The time in which a leader has been in power (Longer leadership = higher risk of coup) 2. The time a regime has been in power (Younger regimes = higher risk of coup) 3. When the last attempt at a coup was (Little time since last coup = high risk of a re-attempt) 4. Defeat in election (Recent defeat = higher risk of coup) 5. Weather conditions (Extreme weather that interfere with agriculture or market dynamics = increased risk of coup) 6. GDPPC (Indicative of a ruling leader’s ability to buy their opponent) I will attempt for the above parameters in relation to the current situation in Venezuela as a basis for my prediction on when Nicolas Maduro will cease to be president of Venezuela.

Update: new developments in Venezuela are cause for reconsidering this question. Yesterday, Guaidò called for an uprising against Maduro at a military base in the capital. Since the self-proclaimed assumption of the interim presidency of Venezuela on 23 January by Juan Guaidó and despite its recognition by more than 50 governments, Maduro’s control over the military and security forces remained largely intact - no regime governors or field generals had switched allegiances. For this reason, I assess that there is only a very little chance (2%) that Maduro will be overturned before April 21, which is in less than one month. In order to have such an outcome, it would be necessary an International intervention. In this regard, Although Trump recently stated that a military option for Venezuela was "not off the table”, before to play the military card the U.S.A would have to face a strong debate, both at the internal and international level. Indeed, the reputation of American interventionism has been strongly affected by the inconclusive and controversial external actions undertaken in recent years (e.g. Iraqi invasion). For this reason, at the internal level, before to intervein Trump would have to convince the parliament that it won’t be the umpteenth huge financial loss without any final benefit in return. At the external level, the Trump’s administration would have to convince the international community that is not another “American attempt of imperialism in the name of democracy” as over the years has been increasingly argued. Furthermore, on a side note, in order to legally legitimize such intervention, a motion should pass in the UN Security Council, where the Russian Federation detain (and is likely to use) the veto power. Yet, there is still the “Uniting for peace” motion (a formula which permits the UN General Assembly to allow a humanitarian intervention in case of an impasse in the Security Council), however it has rarely been used since the born of the United Nation. Therefore, the actual likelihood of American intervention, at least in the short term, is basically low. A fortiori since Russia is defending Nicolas Maduro‘s claim to the presidency in Venezuela and has strong interests in the region. What is more probable is that both Russia and the USA will indirectly sustain the two factions engaging a sort of new proxy War. However, even if such an outcome unfolded, it would require a long and bloody process before a radical political change happens (as it is the case of Assad in Syria who, despite 8 years of civil and proxy war, still holds the power).

Venezuela's self-proclaimed president Juan Guaido yesterday called for two new protests, in an effort to push the military to turn against leader Nicolas Maduro and back a European ultimatum demanding free elections within the week. The head of the opposition-controlled National Assembly said the first of the nationwide strikes, on Wednesday from noon to 2pm, would be one "to demand that the armed forces side with the people." The second, on Saturday, will be a "big national and international rally to back the support of the EU and the ultimatum" that they would recognize Guaido as interim president unless Maduro calls elections by February 3. The U.S. separately warned there would be a "significant response" if U.S. diplomats, Guaido or the National Assembly were targeted with violence and intimidation. Maduro so far has not budged from his position, telling CNN Turk: "No one can give us an ultimatum."

Juan Guaidó, recognised as Venezuela’s interim president by all the major democracies in the Americas apart from Mexico, plans a series of gatherings to consolidate his parallel government. A big demonstration is expected against the regime of Nicolás Maduro, who claims to retain the presidency, after rigging an election last year—and who controls the army and much of government. Mr Maduro’s propaganda machine has been flat-footed in its response to the threat posed by Mr Guaidó. The 35-year-old proclaimed himself president last week, on the basis that Mr Maduro is illegitimate and the head of the national assembly must step in if the presidency is vacant. Mr Maduro initially tried to belittle his rival as “that little boy”. He has since said he is prepared to meet him. On January 26th Mr Maduro delayed by a month his ultimatum that American diplomats must leave the country. Officials in Washington say they do not take orders from “the former President”.
The Netherlands, Germany, France, Spain and Britain are pressing Maduro to hold new elections within eight days, saying they will recognize Guaidó as the interim president otherwise.

Barring some unforeseen events, Maduro will probably stay in power for the foreseeable future. The military seems to be overwhelmingly loyal as multiple coup attempts (or false flags?) have been unsuccessful. Nevertheless, he remains very unpopular and if conditions worsen - which they are likely to do - he might face a more significant threat to his rule than the previous significant protests.

Maduro has faced 3 coups attempts already, and it was reported in September 2018 that the Trump administration had been talking to military officers about a potential coup (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/08/trump-nicolas-maduro-overthrow-venezuelan-meetings). Dictators are generally quite good at keeping power as long as they can spread benefits to allies who help them maintain their power, so Maduro has to keep his allies rolling in the cash from oil, drugs and other illicit activities, but the danger for him is the people who are excluded from this in the military. But they face enormous challenges even if a potential coup succeeds, which may well dissuade them from doing it. (restoring order, fixing the economy, getting control of assets like oil production, dealing with Russia, China and the US as well as people who are about to lose out from the status quo). I think he is likely to survive given all of that.
